      {
        "id": 3154910,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-04-30T16:38:46.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"170338\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>To celebrate a good friend\u2019s birthday , we were invited to a dinner with a lot of great wines . There were many outstanding wines such as VCC 1945 , Latour 82 ( delicious )and Haut Brion 1961 , but everybody\u2019s favorite was Haut Brion 1953 .<br>\nThe wine was dark in color with spices and tobacco on the nose , creamy blue fruit . Still fresh . I read old tasting notes from Parker ( in 93 and 94 ) that he suggests that the wine should be consumed over the near term . But this particular bottle is still going strong , almost 30 years later . Amazing</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>That doesn\u2019t surprise me! Was incredible when I last had it a few years ago, and the most beautifully perfumed Haut Brion I ever drank, with even rose petals joining the classic cuban cigar, loamy soil Haut Brion m\u00e9lange. I\u2019m opening a 1961 next month for my wife\u2019s birthday so it will be interesting to see how that is coming along by comparison.</p>",
        "post_number": 5,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 6,
